In TypeScript, you can use a type assertion to tell the TypeScript compiler that a value has a certain type, even if it is not inferred automatically. This is useful when you know something about the type of a value that the TypeScript compiler does not know.

For example, suppose you have a function that returns an object with multiple possible types, but in practice you know that it will always return an object of a specific type. You can use a type assertion to tell the TypeScript compiler that the value is of that specific type.

Here's an example:

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

interface Admin {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  role: "admin";
}

function getUser(): User | Admin {
  // code to get user or admin data...
}
```
In this example, the `getUser()` function can return either a `User` or an `Admin` object. However, suppose you know that in practice it will always return an `Admin` object. You can use a type assertion to tell the TypeScript compiler that the value is of type `Admin`:
```typescript
const user = getUser() as Admin; // Type assertion
console.log(user.role); // "admin" (no error)
```
In this example, the `as Admin` part of the statement tells the TypeScript compiler that the value returned by `getUser()` is of type `Admin`. The compiler will not check whether the value actually has all the properties of an `Admin` object, so it's important to make sure that the value really is of that type in practice.

